1. Create a tuple for a patient (4 marks)

Tuple format: (Name, Age, Blood Pressure, Heart Rate)

patient = ("John Doe", 45, "120/80", 76)
patient


---

2. Access and print the patientâ€™s age and heart rate (4 marks)

age = patient[1]
heart_rate = patient[3]

print("Age:", age)
print("Heart Rate:", heart_rate)


---

3. Why tuples are suitable for storing patient vitals? (4 marks)

Tuples are suitable because:

They are immutable, meaning the data cannot be accidentally changed.

This protects critical health information from unintentional modification.

They keep related data together in a fixed, structured format.

Faster to access compared to lists because of immutability.


Therefore, tuples are ideal for storing fixed records like patient vitals.


---

4. Convert tuple to list, update heart rate, convert back to tuple (4 marks)

patient_list = list(patient)
patient_list[3] = 80     # updating heart rate
patient = tuple(patient_list)

patient


---

5. Create a tuple of 5 patients and extract all names (4 marks)

patients = (
    ("John Doe", 45, "120/80", 76),
    ("Mary Anne", 39, "118/77", 82),
    ("Kevin Otieno", 50, "130/85", 70),
    ("Sarah Kim", 29, "115/75", 78),
    ("Brian Kip", 60, "140/90", 72)
)

# Extracting all names
names = [p[0] for p in patients]
names


